## How the sliding window works (vs fixed window)

```
Fixed window (naive — has boundary burst problem):
  Window: [0s──────────60s][60s──────────120s]
  Burst:   99 reqs at t=59 + 99 reqs at t=61  →  198 requests in 2 seconds ✗

Sliding window (this implementation):
  At t=61, the window is [1s──────────61s].
  The 99 requests at t=59 are still inside the window, so only 1 more is allowed.
  The window truly slides with each request — no cliff, no boundary burst.   ✓
```

---

## Design notes

| Concern | Decision |
|---|---|
| **Data structure** | `Map<ip, number[]>` — O(1) get/set, iterable for cleanup, no deps |
| **Pruning** | Binary search on the ascending timestamps array → O(log n) find + O(k) copy per request |
| **Reset header** | Points to when the *oldest* in-window timestamp expires, not a fixed clock boundary — gives clients an accurate retry target |
| **Cleanup timer** | `unref()`'d so it never prevents process exit; also exposed via `close()` for explicit teardown in tests |
| **`retryAfter` precision** | `Math.ceil` — always rounds up, so clients never retry too early and get a second 429 |
| **Thread safety** | Node.js is single-threaded, so no mutex needed around the Map |

